summary.seg: Emmanuel College MS 32 is a Miscellany of Greek texts composed of 12 parts, some of which recur in Emmanuel College MS 33.

The first part consists of two damaged quires placed in inverted order. The manuscript from which they came contained, or should have contained, the Idylls of Theocritus of Syracuse, and the margins are ruled to receive the scholia. Part I was copied by Andreas Donos (died before 1560), who also copied Part IV. The latter contain some lines of Theogony (ll. 520-1022) and the Scutum Herculis (ll. 1-238, 400-480) by Hesiod, but the order is disturbed.

Part III consists of four quires from a manuscript of the Alexandra of Lycophoron with scholia by Isaac Tzetzes. The order is disturbed and a fifth quire is now in Emmanuel MS 33, Part II (ff. 95r-[102]). The quire signatures in this part of Emmanuel MS 32 have been trimmed and only two traces remain, but a Greek signature survives in Emmanuel MS 33 (ϛʹ, on ff. 95r and [102]v). From this and the lines of text, it is possible to reconstruct the following quire order:
αʹ = Emmanuel MS 32 quire 7 (+ f. 70)
βʹ = quire 8
γʹ = quire 10
δʹ = missing
εʹ = Emmanuel MS 32 quire 9
ϛʹ = Emmanuel MS 33, Part II.

Part VI contains some carmina of Gregory of Nazianzus from a larger selction known as Gedichtgruppe I. The Carmina de se ipso are copied along with the Paraphase A in two columns. The original order of quires was:
18: ff. 136r-[142]v, 135r-135v
20: ff. [151]r-[158]v
19: ff. 143r-[150]v.

condition.p: In fair condition. The upper corner of ff. 1-[8] has been torn away, a hole is present on ff. 9-[16], the lower margin of f. [188] and outer margin of f. [190] have been cut off, and the outer margin of f. 207 has been torn away.

binding.p: 17th-century pulpboards covered with full leather binding, with plain pastedowns. There is decorative blind tooling on both boards. The former classmark appears on labels.

history.acquisition: The date of acquisition is unknown. It is not listed in Bernard, Catalogi librorum manuscriptorum Angliæ et Hiberniæ (1697).

recordHist.source: Description (2021) draws on M.R. James, The Western manuscripts in the library of Emmanuel College: a descriptive catalogue, Cambridge University Press, Cambridge, 1904, p. 31-34.

availability.p: Visitors to Emmanuel College who wish to consult Special Collections material are required to apply to the Library in advance of their visit. For information on eligibility and admission procedures see: Emmanuel College: Special Collections.

handNote.p: Hand H: cursive mixed minuscule, upright or slightly slanting to the right with marked variation in letter size. Phi has vertical stroke which terminates in a hook. Ligatures and abbreviations are in use mainly at the end of the lines, the iota mutum is in use.
Breathings are curved and do not joint to the accents.

history.origin: The characteristics of the script and the watermarks suggest that this part was produced in the first third of the 16th century.
